### The Revelation and Moral

ଓଡ଼ିଆ ସାରାଂଶ: କିଟୁ ପ୍ରକାଶ କଲା ଯେ ସେ ଦୁଇଟି ଭିନ୍ନ ଚିତ୍ର ଦେଖାଇଥିଲା, ଗୋଟିଏ ବର୍ଷା ପାଇଁ ଏବଂ ଅନ୍ୟଟି ଖରା ପାଇଁ। ବୁଢୀରାମ କେବଳ ଗୋଟିଏ କିଣିଥିଲେ। ଏହି ଘଟଣା ପରେ ବୁଢୀରାମ ଗର୍ବ କରିବା ବନ୍ଦ କରିଦେଲେ।

Kitu calmly explained that he had not cheated Budhiram. He revealed that there were actually *two* paintings: one showing rain with an open umbrella, and another showing sunshine with a closed umbrella. Since Budhiram had only paid half the price, Kitu had only given him one painting. Budhiram did not buy the second picture. From that day onwards, Budhiram stopped boasting about his possessions. The story's **tail-piece** (ଶେଷ ଅଂଶ) reminds us: "The man who thinks himself more clever than others is a fool. World around him is still cleverer."

### Understanding Kitu's Trick

ଓଡ଼ିଆ ସାରାଂଶ: କିଟୁ କିପରି ବୁଢୀରାମଙ୍କୁ ଠକିଲା ତାହା ବୁଝିବା ପାଇଁ ଏହି ଫ୍ଲୋଚାର୍ଟ ଦେଖନ୍ତୁ।

Kitu's trick relied on Budhiram's pride and his assumption that the painting was magical. Here's a simple flow of the events:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Budhiram boasts about wealth] --> B{Kitu plans a trick};
    B --> C[Kitu shows Painting 1 (rain, open umbrella)];
    C --> D[Tea break];
    D --> E[Kitu shows Painting 2 (sun, closed umbrella)];
    E --> F[Budhiram buys Painting 1 (thinking it's magic)];
    F --> G[Budhiram tries to show "magic" to villagers];
    G --> H[Villagers laugh at Budhiram];
    H --> I[Kitu reveals there are two paintings];
```

**Worked Example:**

**Question:** Why did the villagers call Budhiram 'Buduram'?

**Answer:** The villagers called Budhiram 'Buduram' because he was very proud of his wealth and possessions and always talked about them. His constant boasting made them **get bored** (ନିରସ ଲାଗିବା), so they changed his name to 'Buduram' to suggest he was foolish, despite his original name implying wisdom. This shows their annoyance with his **behave** (ବ୍ୟବହାର ଦେଖାଇବା) of showing off. [[2]], [[3]], [[5]]
